In July 2016, the country’s parliament voted against a bill seeking to legalize abortion in cases of rape or incest and in cases where the mother’s life is at risk due to complications with the pregnancy. Further, abortion is not legally available in cases of fetal abnormality, even though a teratologic defect can be fatal, and women can be charged with common law murder if they terminate their pregnancy under these circumstances.

Abortion Legislation

As a member of the British Commonwealth, in July 1979, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines passed a law that made abortion a criminal offense in all cases. Under this law, any woman who illegally terminates a pregnancy may be jailed for up to one year, and anyone else who helped in the abortion may receive a sentence of five years. Since July 1979, the nation has not changed its criminal code regarding women’s access to abortion.^1 In addition, if women in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines obtain an abortion outside the country without a passport, it is illegal to bring the abortion medication (ie, misoprostol, mifepristone) into the country. Women who are found with abortion medication without any proof of medical necessity could be prosecuted. No study has been conducted to help inform the court on the status of a woman giving birth to an unhealthy fetus.
